  <h2 id="faqs">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

  <h3>Is Cigna Global or Allianz Care better?</h3>
  <p>
    Neither is universally better—it depends on your priorities. Cigna Global offers superior network access and digital experience but costs more. Allianz Care provides better value and mental health coverage but may require more claims paperwork. The best choice depends on your specific needs, budget, and location.
  </p>

  <h3>Why is Cigna Global more expensive than Allianz Care?</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna invests heavily in their provider network and direct billing relationships, which costs money but creates convenience. They also offer an industry-leading digital experience and strong customer service. Allianz operates more efficiently with a reimbursement-focused model. The price difference reflects these different business approaches.
  </p>

  <h3>Which provider has better mental health coverage?</h3>
  <p>
    Allianz Care has clearly better mental health coverage. They offer enhanced benefits with more generous session limits and better coverage for ongoing treatment. Cigna covers mental health but with more limitations that may not suffice for sustained treatment needs.
  </p>

  <h3>Can I switch from one provider to the other?</h3>
  <p>
    Yes, you can switch at any renewal period. However, switching triggers new underwriting, and any conditions that developed while on your previous policy could be treated as pre-existing by the new insurer. Consider this carefully before switching, especially if you've developed health issues while covered.
  </p>

  <h3>Which provider is better for families?</h3>
  <p>
    Cigna Global is often recommended for families due to their strong family plan options, good maternity coverage, and emphasis on convenience—parents have enough to deal with without health insurance paperwork. Allianz is also suitable for families, particularly budget-conscious ones, but may involve more administrative work.
  </p>

  <h3>How do these providers handle pre-existing conditions?</h3>
  <p>
    Both offer moratorium and full medical underwriting options. Cigna typically excludes pre-existing conditions initially with potential coverage after a moratorium period. Allianz may be slightly more willing to offer coverage with premium loadings rather than outright exclusions. Apply to both and compare specific terms offered for your conditions.
  </p>

